-- Sensitive Index Climbs on Growth Outlook; Tata Motors, Sterlite Lead Gains
-- B y   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-10-11T11:12:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-11/sensex-index-advances-on-growth-outlook-tata-motors-sterlite-lead-gains.html
India’s stocks rose as investors
judged the outlook for domestic consumption will remain robust,
buoying company earnings.  Tata Motors Ltd. , the biggest truckmaker and owner of
Jaguar Land Rover, climbed for the first day in three.  Sterlite
Industries (India) Ltd.  advanced with raw material prices amid
speculation the U.S. Federal Reserve will act to further
stimulate economic growth. The rupee gained 5 percent against
the dollar in the past month as global funds pumped a record $21
billion into Indian stocks this year on optimism about the South
Asian’s nation’s growth prospects.  “Global money will continue to pour into Indian markets,”
said  Sadanand Shetty , a Mumbai-based fund manager at Taurus
Asset Management Co., which manages $665 million in assets.
“Companies which are directly or indirectly linked to domestic
consumption are looking good.”  The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
gained 89.63, or 0.4 percent, to 20,339.89 as of the 3:30 p.m.
close in Mumbai. The gauge has gained 27 percent from a May 25
low, approaching the record closing high of 20,873.33 on Jan. 8,
2008. The gauge is the best performer this year among the
world’s 10 biggest stock markets. The measure climbed 12 percent
last month, the most since May 2009.  Tata Motors  The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on the National Stock Exchange rose
0.5 percent to 6,135.85. The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.6 percent
to 2593.17. India’s biggest companies will announce their
September quarter result this week.  Tata Motors, maker of the world’s cheapest car, the Nano,
surged 4.4 percent to 1,151.6 rupees. Hero Honda Motors Ltd.,
India’s largest motorcycle maker, gained 1.6 percent to 1,874.2
rupees.  Sterlite rose 3.3 percent to 179.7 rupees. Copper for
three-month delivery on the London Metal Exchange rose as much
as 3.1 percent, the highest level since July 2008.  Tata Steel Ltd. , the nation’s biggest producer, gained 2.2
percent to 640.1 rupees.  “The Indian economy is fundamentally strong, which is
being reflected in stock prices and fund flows,” said  Tejas Doshi , vice president of equity research at Sushil Financial
Services Pvt. in Mumbai.  Overseas  funds  bought a net  17 billion rupees  ($384.1
million) of Indian equities on Oct. 7 for the 27th straight day,
extending this year’s record inflows to 979.6 billion rupees,
according to the nation’s market regulator.  ----With assistance from  Hemal Savai  in Mumbai. Editors: Margo
